 state—imports resolved, code executed, side effects visible—before onLoad is called. A unit test with mocked require() can only verify call order, not actual module initialization. Mocking always returns a fake module, which hides the real failure: a loader that calls onLoad before the module's require() completes. Integration testing with real plugin modules (with observable side effects or exports) reveals whether the loader respects actual Node.js module loading semantics.","test_description":"Create a real plugin module that exports a marker object (e.g., { initialized: true }) and performs a side effect (e.g., sets a module-level flag). Configure the loader to load this plugin. Before the loader invokes the plugin's onLoad hook, inspect the module's exports and verify that the side effect has occurred. Assert that the module state is consistent with successful require() execution.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Integration testing with real modules is necessary to verify module readiness. Does not test filesystem errors; assumes modules load cleanly from a test directory or in-memory source.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When a plugin throws an error during its onLoad hook, the loader continues initializing the remaining plugins that do not depend on it.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Error handling and dependency-aware skipping are control-flow decisions. Real failure (crashing on error, skipping non-dependent plugins incorrectly) is observable by mocking plugin hooks with one hook throwing an exception. Verify that the loader catches the error, does not call onLoad for dependent plugins, calls onLoad for non-dependent plugins, and continues without crashing. Mocks will not hide this; if the loader crashes or makes wrong calls, the test execution will show it.","test_description":"Create three plugin manifests: A (onLoad throws), B (depends on A), and C (independent). Mock the hooks so A.onLoad raises an exception. Invoke the loader and assert: (1) A.onLoad is called and throws, (2) B.onLoad is never called, (3) C.onLoad is called successfully, and (4) the loader completes without crashing.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Tests control-flow logic (exception handling, dependency skipping). Assumes exception handling is straightforward and does not depend on actual plugin code behavior.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.65,"Integration":0.25,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.05}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13493,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13493},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8e3f6abb-31bc-4936-b7f3-7bde9d9d9538","uuid":"3204d3fb-c804-44bc-a233-84d324d9fca7"}
